    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Workflow automation</strong> is the use of software to automatically execute a defined series of tasks or business processes based on triggers, rules, and conditions — with little or no human intervention. In marketing, it replaces repetitive manual work: sending follow-up emails, assigning leads to the right rep, updating CRM records, posting social content on schedule, and sending review requests after purchase. It runs continuously, error-free, at a scale no human team can match.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Process Automation, BPA</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every repetitive task your marketing team does manually — copying lead data from a form into a CRM, sending a follow-up email 24 hours after a demo, tagging contacts by behaviour — can be automated. The question is never whether to automate but where to start and how to build automations that scale without breaking.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is workflow automation?</h2>
        <p>A workflow is a sequence of tasks that accomplishes a business goal. Workflow automation replaces the human actions in that sequence with software that executes the tasks automatically, triggered by events and guided by rules.</p>
        <p>Every automated workflow has three core components:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Trigger</strong> — the event that starts the workflow (form submission, email open, deal stage change, date/time, API call)</li>
          <li><strong>Action</strong> — what the software does in response (send email, update field, create task, add tag, post to Slack)</li>
          <li><strong>Conditions</strong> — if/then logic that branches the workflow based on data (if lead score is above 80, route to sales; if below, add to nurture sequence)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>String multiple triggers, conditions, and actions together and you have a workflow that handles a complete business process — without a human touching it between start and finish.</p>

        <h2 id="examples">Workflow automation examples in marketing</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Workflow</th><th>Trigger</th><th>Actions</th><th>Tool</th></tr>
            </thead>
